SECTION 1: PROJECT OVERVIEW
1.1 Executive Summary
Project Name: MediTrack - Medicine Anti-Counterfeit Tracking System

Problem Statement: Counterfeit pharmaceuticals cause 10-15% contamination in medicine supply chains across developing nations, leading to hundreds of thousands of preventable deaths annually. Recent incidents include:

Gambia (2022): 70+ children died from contaminated cough syrup
Uzbekistan (2022): 18 children died from similar incident
India: Multiple cases of fake cancer drugs, antibiotics
The root cause: Lack of infrastructure to track medicines from production to patient.

Solution: MediTrack creates a digital identity for every medicine package using unique serial numbers and Data Matrix barcodes, enabling complete traceability and real-time verification at every checkpoint in the supply chain.

Key Innovation: Individual package-level tracking (not just batch tracking) + Hierarchical QR system (box-level convenience + individual-level security) + Mandatory pharmacy verification checkpoint.

1.2 Project Scope
In Scope (MVP - Minimum Viable Product):
✅ Manufacturer portal (product registration, serial generation, QR creation)
✅ Pharmacy portal (barcode scanning, verification, dispensing)
✅ Patient verification app (PWA - Progressive Web App)
✅ Basic regulatory dashboard (statistics, alerts)
✅ Central database with verification logic
✅ Hierarchical tracking (individual medicine + box level)
✅ Camera-based barcode scanning
✅ Real-time counterfeit detection
✅ Simple alert system

1.3 Success Criteria
The MVP is considered successful if it demonstrates:

Functional Completeness:
Can generate 1000+ unique serial numbers
Can create scannable QR codes
Can verify medicines in < 2 seconds
Can detect duplicate/invalid codes
Can track medicine status (manufactured → dispensed)
User Experience:
Manufacturer can generate serials in < 5 clicks
Pharmacy can scan and verify in < 3 seconds
Patient can verify via smartphone camera
Clear visual feedback (green/red for genuine/fake)
Technical Performance:
Database handles 10,000+ records smoothly
API response time < 200ms
Zero data loss (all transactions logged)
Works on common browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari)
Demonstration Capability:
Can show complete flow: manufacturer → pharmacy → patient
Can demonstrate counterfeit detection (invalid code, duplicate code)
Can show regulatory dashboard with statistics
SECTION 2: REAL-WORLD CONTEXT & MOTIVATION
2.1 The Global Counterfeit Medicine Crisis
Statistics:
WHO estimate: 10-15% of medicines in developing countries are counterfeit
Annual deaths: ~1 million people die from fake medicines
Economic impact: $200 billion lost annually
Regional impact: Up to 30% of medicines in some African/Asian regions are fake
Real Incidents:
Case 1: Gambia Cough Syrup Tragedy (2022)

What happened: 70+ children died after consuming cough syrup
Cause: Syrup contained diethylene glycol (industrial chemical, toxic)
Root problem: No tracking system to trace origin or recall quickly
Outcome: International scandal, WHO investigation
Case 2: Fake Cancer Drugs (USA, 2012)

What happened: Counterfeit Avastin (cancer drug) entered US supply chain
Content: Contained no active ingredient - just salt, starch, cleaning solvents
Impact: Cancer patients received ineffective treatment, some died
Cost: Millions in damages, loss of trust
Case 3: Fake Antimalarials (Africa, ongoing)

Scale: Widespread across sub-Saharan Africa
Content: No active ingredient or wrong dosages
Impact: Contributed to malaria deaths, drug-resistant strains
Estimate: 30% of antimalarials in some regions are fake
Why Current Systems Fail:
Bulk tracking only: Track batches, not individual packages
No verification point: Pharmacies can't verify authenticity
Manual processes: Paper-based records, easily forged
Slow recalls: Takes weeks/months to locate affected medicines
No patient empowerment: Patients have no way to verify
2.2 Turkey's Success Story (ITS System)
Background:
Turkey implemented İlaç Takip Sistemi (ITS) in 2010 to combat widespread counterfeit medicines.

How It Works:
Every prescription medicine gets a unique Data Matrix barcode
Manufacturers upload serial numbers to central government database
Pharmacies must scan before dispensing (mandatory by law)
System verifies in real-time (1-2 seconds)
Patients can verify via mobile app or website
Results (2010-Present):
90%+ reduction in counterfeit medicines
100% of prescription medicines tracked
12,000+ pharmacies connected
Billions of verifications performed
Faster recalls: Hours instead of weeks
Increased patient confidence
Key Success Factors:
Mandatory scanning at pharmacy (enforced by law)
Government-run central database (single source of truth)
Real-time verification (instant feedback)
Simple user interface (pharmacists can use easily)
Patient verification option (empowerment)
Why We Use Turkey as Model:
Proven effectiveness (90%+ reduction)
Scalable (works at national level)
Cost-effective (reasonable infrastructure costs)
Replicable (can be adapted to other countries)
Well-documented (implementation details available)
SECTION 3: SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS ANALYSIS
3.1 Functional Requirements
FR1: Manufacturer Functions
FR1.1 Product Registration

Input: Product name, generic name, GTIN, dosage, strength, form, regulatory approval number
Process: Validate GTIN format, check for duplicates, store in database
Output: Unique product ID, confirmation message
FR1.2 Serial Number Generation (Hierarchical)

Input: Product ID, batch number, quantity, manufacturing date, expiry date, box size (default 100)
Process:
Generate unique serial numbers using cryptographic algorithm
Format: [YEAR]-[MFR_CODE]-[PRODUCT_CODE]-[SEQUENCE]
Example: 2024-PFZ-ASP-0001234
Create box records (every 100 medicines = 1 box)
Each box gets unique ID: BOX-2024-001
Output:
List of serial numbers
Box IDs with contents mapping
Downloadable CSV file
FR1.3 QR Code Generation

Input: Serial numbers, product details
Process:
Generate GS1-compliant Data Matrix barcode
Format: (01)GTIN(21)Serial(17)ExpDate(10)Batch
Create two types:
Individual QR: For each medicine package
Box QR: For shipping boxes (contains list of 100 serials)
Output:
QR code images (PNG, 200x200 pixels)
Printable PDF with all codes
High error correction level (Level H)
FR2: Pharmacy Functions
FR2.1 Box-Level Receipt (Convenience)

Input: Box QR code scan
Process:
Decode box QR → Extract box ID
Look up box in database
Verify: Box exists, status = "at_wholesaler", not tampered
Update all 100 medicines: status = "at_pharmacy", location = pharmacy ID
Log transaction (box receive)
Output:
Success message: "✅ Received 100 medicines from Box-2024-001"
List of serial numbers received
Inventory updated
FR2.2 Individual Medicine Verification (CRITICAL - Mandatory)

Input: Individual medicine QR code scan
Process:
Decode QR → Extract serial number
Perform multi-layer verification:
Existence check: Does serial exist in database?
Duplicate check: Already dispensed elsewhere?
Expiry check: Past expiration date?
Recall check: Part of recalled batch?
Location check: Currently at this pharmacy?
Based on checks, determine result
Output:
If ALL checks pass: ✅ "Genuine medicine - Safe to dispense"
If ANY check fails: ❌ "COUNTERFEIT/WARNING" with specific reason
Display: Product name, batch, expiry, manufacturer, status
FR2.3 Medicine Dispensing

Input: Verified serial number, pharmacist ID, patient info (optional)
Process:
Update medicine status: "at_pharmacy" → "dispensed"
Record: dispensed_at (timestamp), dispensed_by (pharmacist ID)
Log transaction (dispense action)
Lock serial number (cannot be reused)
Output:
Confirmation message
Updated inventory count
Transaction receipt (optional)
FR3: Patient Functions
FR3.1 Medicine Verification (Camera Scan)

Input: Medicine QR code (via smartphone camera)
Process:
Camera scans QR code using html5-qrcode library
Decode → Extract serial number
Send to verification API
Receive verification result
Output:
If genuine:
✅ "VERIFIED GENUINE MEDICINE"
Product details (name, manufacturer, batch, expiry)
Journey timeline (Factory → Wholesaler → Pharmacy)
Dispensing details (date, pharmacy name)
If fake:
❌ "WARNING: POSSIBLE COUNTERFEIT"
Reason (serial not found, duplicate, etc.)
"Do NOT use. Report to authorities."
Report button
FR3.2 SMS Verification (Alternative for Basic Phones)

Input: Serial number typed manually
Process: Same as camera scan
Output: Text-based result (simplified)
Note: For MVP, simulate SMS (actual SMS gateway in phase 2)
FR4: Regulatory Dashboard Functions
FR4.1 Real-Time Monitoring

Display:
Total medicines tracked
Verifications today/this hour
Success vs. failure rate
Active pharmacies
Geographic distribution (simple map or list)
FR4.2 Alert Management

Trigger alerts for:
Invalid serial number scanned
Duplicate serial number detected
Multiple failures from same pharmacy (suspicious pattern)
Alert information:
Alert type, severity, timestamp
Serial number involved
Pharmacy/location
GPS coordinates (if available)
Actions:
View alert details
Mark as investigating/resolved
Generate report
FR4.3 Recall Management (Basic)

Input: Product ID or batch number
Process:
Mark all medicines in batch as "recalled"
Block dispensing (pharmacy cannot sell)
Identify locations (where medicines currently are)
Generate list of affected pharmacies
Output:
Recall summary (total affected, current locations)
List of pharmacies to contact
Tracking dashboard (how many returned)
3.2 Non-Functional Requirements
NFR1: Performance
Response Time: API calls < 200ms (95th percentile)
Verification Speed: < 2 seconds from scan to result
Concurrent Users: Support 100 simultaneous verifications
Database Queries: Indexed queries < 50ms
NFR2: Scalability
Data Volume: Handle 100,000+ serial numbers
Growth: Design supports 10x growth without architecture changes
Auto-scaling: Plan for horizontal scaling (multiple servers)
NFR3: Reliability
Uptime: 99% availability target
Data Integrity: Zero data loss (all transactions logged)
Error Handling: Graceful degradation (if cache fails, use database)
NFR4: Security
Authentication: JWT-based with secure password hashing (bcrypt)
Authorization: Role-based access (manufacturer, pharmacy, regulator)
Data Protection: HTTPS for all communications
SQL Injection: Use parameterized queries (prevent injection)
XSS Prevention: Sanitize user inputs
NFR5: Usability
Mobile Responsive: Works on phones, tablets, laptops
Browser Support: Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge
Load Time: Pages load < 3 seconds
Accessibility: Clear visual feedback (green/red indicators)
NFR6: Maintainability
Code Quality: Clean code, documented functions
Version Control: Git with meaningful commit messages
Documentation: API documentation, setup guide
Modular Design: Separate concerns (routes, services, database)
